bug.short_desc: Evolution doing pending background operations for a long time

long_desc.thetext:
Created attachment 1155885 screenshot
Description of problem: Evolution doing pending background operations for a long time
Version-Release number of selected component (if applicable): $ rpm -qa | grep evolution | sort evolution-3.20.1-1.fc24.x86_64 evolution-data-server-3.20.1-2.fc24.x86_64 evolution-data-server-debuginfo-3.20.1-2.fc24.x86_64 evolution-debuginfo-3.20.1-1.fc24.x86_64 evolution-ews-3.20.1-3.fc24.x86_64 evolution-ews-debuginfo-3.20.1-3.fc24.x86_64 evolution-help-3.20.1-1.fc24.noarch
How reproducible: After long uptime close Evolution

Thanks for a bug report. I see in the backtrace a deadlock in the IMAP code, partly related to the glib2 version, it seems to me, even I do not see any related change in the GCancellable code.
As a side note, did you install the Fedora from scratch, or you did an update on a machine which already had evolution running? The console shows: > e_mail_remote_content_set_config_filename: Failed to open '/home/mikhail/ > .config/evolution/mail/remote-content.db': unable to open database file > > e_mail_properties_set_config_filename: Failed to open '/home/mikhail/.config > /evolution/mail/properties.db': unable to open database file
It can be that either the ~/.config/evolution/mail/ folder doesn't exist or both of the files are protected for opening. Could you verify which of the two is true (or what else broke there), please?

I found out that this issue is fixed in the evolution-data-server 3.20.2, which had been released on Monday. It should be available in updates-testing very soon. It's part of this update: https://bodhi.fedoraproject.org/updates/FEDORA-2016-e544bef3ed
The corresponding upstream commit is: https://git.gnome.org/browse/evolution-data-server/commit/?h=gnome-3-20&id=b59863d88

> As a side note, did you install the Fedora from scratch, or you did an > update on a machine which already had evolution running? > > It can be that either the ~/.config/evolution/mail/ folder doesn't exist or > both of the files are protected for opening. (I tired from brakes of btrfs which no one want fix), but when moving, I did not copy the .config folder, ie can be shure that all settings are fresh, as if the system is newly installed. Of course after it I reboot system several times and restore SELinux labels by restorecon -vR /
